[In March 2012, 2 months ago, there was a report of a distemper outbreak in raccoons from another area of Ontario (see ProMED post 20120316.1072492).

As distemper and rabies affect the central nervous system, they both cause behavior disorders. In raccoons, distemper usually results in stumbling and lack of 'shyness', they can seem 'dumb' and/or 'friendly.' Rabid raccoons also might lose their fear of humans and other animals and they fall into stupor and may become slower, but they show profuse salivation, indiscriminate biting and odd vocalization.

It is very important to make sure to keep the [rabies & distemper] vaccination schemes of all dogs in the area up to date.

For a video of a raccoon with distemper go to
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H22KFjDnY08&feature=related.
A map of the affected area can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/2oGh - Mod.PMB]
